{
  "text": "A look at the transient absorption data in figure 2 reveals a signal decay in |\u03b2 on a timescale of 100 fs. The product state is not unambiguously identified but |g can be excluded, since then |\u03b1 would need to show a similar signal decay: a populated ground state would enable reexcitation into both |\u03b1 and |\u03b2 [CITATION_1] . A reasonable assumption within the model is a population transfer from |\u03b2 to |\u03b1 , which would lead to an increased excited-state absorption into the two-exciton state | f . Looking at the behavior in |\u03b1 , only a small Stokes shift or a vanishing SE signal on a femtosecond timescale is directly observable, but the amount of bleaching stays roughly the same over the entire delay time. This evidences that the ground state is not repopulated during the experiment.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "5631677"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "5631677": {
      "title": "Ultrafast exciton dynamics after Soret-or Q-band excitation of a directly \u03b2, \u03b2 -linked bisporphyrin",
      "abstract": "We report on a comprehensive transient absorption study with \u03b2,\u03b2'-linked bis[tetraphenylporphyrinato-zinc(II)] and its corresponding monomer, covering the ultrafast dynamics from femtoseconds up to several microseconds. By exciting these porphyrins either to their first (S(1)) or second (S(2)) electronically excited states and by probing the subsequent dynamics, a multitude of reaction pathways have been identified. In the spectral region associated with the ground-state recovery of the bisporphyrin, transient absorption changes occur within the first few picoseconds, which are ascribable to excitonic interaction both in the S(2) (fs time-domain) and in the S(1) (ps time-domain) state. This is substantiated by complementary experiments with the monomeric porphyrin, in which the S(2) state exhibits a longer lifetime. In contrast to the picosecond dynamics the bisporphyrin and the monomer behave similarly on the nanosecond time-scale, that is nearly all excited molecules eventually reach a long-lived triplet excited state."
    }
  }
}